Detect Ransomware Precursors in Memory Artifacts
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Analyze memory dumps to identify ransomware signatures and indicators
Detect precursor activities that lead to ransomware deployment
Use open-source memory forensics tools to investigate malicious processes
Correlate memory artifacts with ransomware attack patterns
Prerequisites
Basic understanding of Linux command line
Familiarity with process management concepts
Knowledge of file systems and memory structures
Understanding of malware analysis fundamentals
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated environment. The provided Linux machine is bare metal with no pre-installed tools, so you will install all required tools during the lab exercises.

Task 1: Analyze Memory Artifacts for Ransomware Signatures
Subtask 1.1: Install Required Tools
Install Volatility3 and supporting tools for memory analysis:

# Update system packages
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

# Install Python and pip
sudo apt install python3 python3-pip git wget -y

# Install Volatility3
git clone https://github.com/volatilityfoundation/volatility3.git
cd volatility3
pip3 install -r requirements.txt
sudo python3 setup.py install

# Install additional forensics tools
sudo apt install binwalk hexdump strings -y

# Verify installation
python3 vol.py --help
Subtask 1.2: Create Sample Memory Dump
Generate a memory dump for analysis:

# Create working directory
mkdir ~/ransomware_analysis
cd ~/ransomware_analysis

# Install LiME (Linux Memory Extractor)
git clone https://github.com/504ensicsLabs/LiME.git
cd LiME/src
make

# Create memory dump
sudo insmod lime-$(uname -r).ko "path=~/ransomware_analysis/memory.lime format=lime"

# Verify dump creation
ls -lh ~/ransomware_analysis/memory.lime
Subtask 1.3: Analyze Process List
Examine running processes for suspicious activity:

cd ~/ransomware_analysis

# List all processes
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.pslist

# Look for suspicious process names
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.pslist | grep -E "(crypt|lock|ransom|encrypt)"

# Check process tree
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.pstree
Subtask 1.4: Examine Network Connections
Identify suspicious network activity:

# Check network connections
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.netstat

# Look for connections to suspicious IPs or ports
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.netstat | grep -E "(443|80|8080|4444)"
Subtask 1.5: Search for Ransomware Strings
Look for common ransomware indicators in memory:

# Extract strings from memory dump
strings memory.lime > memory_strings.txt

# Search for ransomware-related strings
grep -i "encrypt\|ransom\|bitcoin\|decrypt\|payment\|restore" memory_strings.txt | head -20

# Search for file extension patterns
grep -E "\.(locked|encrypted|crypto|vault)" memory_strings.txt | head -10

# Look for ransom note keywords
grep -i "your files\|pay\|bitcoin\|restore\|decrypt" memory_strings.txt | head -15
Task 2: Identify Precursor Actions Leading to Ransomware Attacks
Subtask 2.1: Analyze File System Activity
Examine file operations that precede ransomware deployment:

# Check for recently modified files
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.mount

# Look for suspicious file handles
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.lsof | grep -E "\.(exe|bat|ps1|vbs)"
Subtask 2.2: Investigate Process Command Lines
Examine command line arguments for malicious activity:

# Extract command line arguments
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.cmdline

# Look for PowerShell or script execution
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.cmdline | grep -E "(powershell|cmd|bash|python)"

# Search for download activities
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.cmdline | grep -E "(wget|curl|download)"
Subtask 2.3: Examine Memory Sections
Analyze memory sections for injected code:

# Check memory mappings
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.proc.Maps

# Look for executable memory regions
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.proc.Maps | grep -E "r-x|rwx"
Subtask 2.4: Detect Privilege Escalation
Identify attempts to gain elevated privileges:

# Check for SUID processes
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.pslist | grep -E "(root|sudo)"

# Look for capability changes
python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.capabilities
Subtask 2.5: Create Analysis Report
Document findings and create a comprehensive report:

# Create analysis report
cat > ransomware_analysis_report.txt << EOF
RANSOMWARE PRECURSOR ANALYSIS REPORT
====================================

Date: $(date)
Memory Dump: memory.lime
Size: $(ls -lh memory.lime | awk '{print $5}')

SUSPICIOUS PROCESSES:
$(python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.pslist | grep -E "(crypt|lock|ransom|encrypt)" || echo "None detected")

NETWORK CONNECTIONS:
$(python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.netstat | head -10)

RANSOMWARE INDICATORS:
$(grep -i "encrypt\|ransom\|bitcoin" memory_strings.txt | head -5 || echo "None found")

RECOMMENDATIONS:
- Monitor processes with encryption-related names
- Block suspicious network connections
- Implement file integrity monitoring
- Regular memory analysis for early detection

EOF

# Display report
cat ransomware_analysis_report.txt
Subtask 2.6: Verify Analysis Results
Validate findings and ensure completeness:

# Count total processes analyzed
echo "Total processes: $(python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.pslist | wc -l)"

# Count network connections
echo "Network connections: $(python3 ~/volatility3/vol.py -f memory.lime linux.netstat | wc -l)"

# Count suspicious strings found
echo "Suspicious strings: $(grep -i "encrypt\|ransom\|bitcoin" memory_strings.txt | wc -l)"

# Create summary
echo "Analysis completed successfully. Check ransomware_analysis_report.txt for detailed findings."
